Those look like they were crowded out when the landowner planted another dense conifer as natural fencing (plus the red cedar should have been thinned at some point). column18:
I live in a HOA that has a greenbelt of about two hundred acres. Cedars that were large and healthy have been dying. We removed about eighty trees last year that suddenly died and we removed seventy more this year. This year the dead tree list also had hemlocks. I think we will lose all of our hemlocks soon and many, many of our cedars have thin tops, dead tops, or just up and died. The dead trees are of all sizes from a yard or more in diameter to ten inches. The die off started in the more moist areas of the greenbelt but is spreading. 
The greenbelt is in what is essentially a housing development but there are rules to protect trees. The ground varies from dry to wet. There are areas that probably should never have been platted due to wetness.  The ground has a gradual slope.

Rocky ridge, thin topsoil. This tree has the top 3/4 dead, and the lower branches have thin canopy. At least 10 other cedars in the area in similar condition, some outright dead. There are also a few pines (at least 4 that I saw) within sight that are dead or have many dead branches.

column18: Observed dieback while jogging along FS Road 388 between Hoodoo Creek and N Fork Trout Creek.  We saw rusty dead cedar needles in the trees we were jogging along the south side of the canyon, but also (and primarily) looking north across the canyon wherein we noted the dieback and orange discoloration at a fairly large scale.  Saw a range of severity, from entire trees to branch dieback.

column60: Two trees appear to have expanded into each other at ground level. This observation is about the trunk on the right in photos with both trunks. They are within a few feet of another, separate Western Redcedar, which is also reported in the Western Redcedar Dieback Map: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/134931662. The tops of all three trees show in the overall canopy photo; this observation is about the one in the center of that photo. Tree does not show any tip dieback. It appears to have normal dieback of interior shaded branches, shown in one photo. There is also one small branch in the canopy with dead leaves shown in a canopy photo; it is probably from something breaking it, not dieback from stress.

column60: This tree (as shown) was cut back for the sake of the path beneath its canopy. Otherwise, it appears to be fairly healthy. It is growing up a slope from a stream that flows with at least a trickle of water year round. There is little visible damage on this tree besides the trimming for the trail. As for other species' health, this forest is fairly healthy. There are very few dead snags besides those that have fallen in the recent windstorms we've been experiencing. However, I do believe that this forest could be at risk in the future due to the abundance of invasive himalayan blackberry and english ivy, which have choked out some native wildflower species. The ivy has started to climb nearby bigleaf maples, red alders, and douglas firs and should be removed to prevent harm to these trees.

column18:
For up to 3 years... we've noticed a dieback in the tops of an ever-increasing number of mature Western Redcedars in our immediate vicinity.
However, within the past year we've noticed that many trees in the immediate vicinity and the larger greater community (15mi radius) have redding/browning foliage and are NOT recovering. It is NOT just along roads and of particular note... even trees have or are very near to year-round visible surface water have been affected, however those with a south exposure and on ridges are severely affected.
We suspect the massive dieback was triggered by the heat dome of 2021 (persistent 113F) and exacerbated by drought over the last few years.
Dieback is also detected in a few firs and lodgepole pine... but NOT ubiquitous like the cedars.

column60: I grew up in Oregon and have traveled extensively in the Pacific Northwest and I've never seen anything like this before. Now that I'm acutely aware of the problem, I'm noticing the foliage browning / dieback everywhere, both here in Canada, along the entire corridor to Portland, and in my home town.

column60: These trees are all on our property. Several have had dead canopies for 15 to 20 years and some are much newer. One old one is next to a road and a newer one is near our driveway and has some brownish leaf ends. We have a large area of wooded land that backs up to a King County open space. Several of the trees are in this area. There is a gentle slope to the land and it is quite wet in the winter months particularly. There's evidence of sap sucker around woodpecker holes on some of the trees. The big leave maple trees are in the process of dying or dead and there are a few firs that are dying and the bark is peeling. We have several Western road cedars that are enormous and would take many people to wrap arms around the base of the trunk..

column18:
My property has several Red Cedars which have been displaying thinning top canopy and die back.  I lost 6 over the past few years that I had taken down within the passt month.  Last year three of the dying trees grew an extensive amount of white fungus on the lower trunks.  I've also seen bore hole in some of the trees.

An arborist said that when the trees are stressed by excessive heat they are suseptable t beetle infestation and I suppose fungus as well.

Trying to save the cedars I have left.

column18:
Just an example, red cedars all around the lake have tops with dieback.  Except for those that were completely dead they all seemed to be red cedars , and the larger taller ones in particular I would say at least 2/3 res have dieback.  The old growth trail has allot of water and some very large trees, red cedars, hemlocks some really large Doug Fir (but few young Doug Fir). So not sure why the dieback, less water, just old, high winter winds . . .Some parts of the lake have more Hemlocks, or Doug Fir etc.

This photo is actually 4 photos merged together the bottom is dark because I used the same exposure for all of them.
column60: The trail is lake side, some areas have board walk because they are wet or to protect the trees.  Too much water is a possibility or maybe lack of water if lake is low etc. I think one tree out say 50 had holes from a wood pecker holes. I did report on a few trees here last year but that was just near the cabin we stayed in and the general store / boat launch.  Did not crane my head up when hiking last year with relatives to see the top .

column60: Where the apartments are was a forest which was mostly removed between summer 2018 and 2019 to put in the apartments. Neighbors fought to keep some of the forest (~50'). The trees closer to the neighborhood then became more exposed to sun and wind load that they had not experienced before. So far we have had at least 5 WRC have to come down due to death, with quite a few more likely to be impacted. When the trees have come down, I observed in the wood/ under the bark significant insect galleries. I would be happy to share photos if desired or samples of the wood.

column60: This tree and the other WRC nearby have lost significant shelter from adjacent forest due to development downslope. There used to be wetlands and a pretty significant forest in the surrounding areas to the west. They now get the hot afternoon sun with little protection in the summer. I have observed this tree and others nearby as I walk the adjacent trail daily. Many Big leaf maples along this cooridor have come down or were removed due to safety concerns post development possibly due to wind load and loss of adjacent forest protection.
